gned the defective hinge design. The second big thing is the improved battery recharge times, which I have not yet seen anyone comment on, only 1h 10mins from 0% to 80% charge. Below is the list of improvements I have experience over the first seven battery cycles.</p>\r\n<p align=\"left\"><strong>improvements</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">1. battery - up from 3 hours to 5 hours (real usage times)\r\n2. battery recharging is faster, takes 2 hours for a full charge - 50% improvement\r\n3. screen res increased and screen is thinner (1280x800 -&gt; 1440x900)\r\n4. new hinge design making the back-end of the laptop thicker\r\n5. cooler laptop, hinge is the air vent which works very well\r\n6. 4gig ram option (100% increase)\r\n7. 256gig flash drive option (100% increase)\r\n8. new glass touch pad with button in pad\r\n9. faster graphics card (you can feel the improvement when surfing and scrolling)\r\n10. no flap for usb\r\n11. 2x USB, mini display port, and a SD card reader\r\n12. F-keys changed to include power button so sound keys are off set by one key\r\n13. faster rebooting, about three times faster\r\n14. memory stick for install disk (no more dvd\r\n15. speaker are louder<strong>\r\n\r\nmissing</strong>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">1. light senor removed\r\n2. backlit keyboard removed\r\n3. no 3G modem (previous models did not have 3G)\r\n4. standby light removed\r\n<p align=\"left\"><strong>links</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\"><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacBook_Air\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacBook_Air</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.engadget.com/2010/10/26/macbook-air-review-late-2010/\"> http://www.engadget.com/2010/10/26/macbook-air-review-late-2010/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/MacBook-Air-11-Inch-Model-A1370-Teardown/3745/1\"> http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/MacBook-Air-11-Inch-Model-A1370-Teardown/3745/1</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.photofast.tw/products/GM2_SFV1_Air.html\"> http://www.photofast.tw/products/GM2_SFV1_Air.html</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.apple.com/au/macbookair/\"> http://www.apple.com/au/macbookair/</a>\r\n<p align=\"left\">Christiaan Hunter</p>',0,0,3,'publish','open','http://www.crashzone.com.au/2010/11/05/apple-macbook-air-2010-13-inch-review-new-hinge/','2010-11-05 13:22:37','2010-11-07 14:35:26',NULL),(2107,'Oxford Funding - The tailored debtor finance specialist','oxford-funding-the-tailored-debtor-finance-specialist','Oxford Funding - The tailored debtor finance specialist','<img src=\"http://www.crashzone.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/oxford-funding.jpg\" alt=\"OXFORD FUNDING - The tailored debtor finance specialist\" />\r\n<p align=\"left\">Do you wish your insurance and corporate fleet invoices would get paid more quickly?</p>\r\n<p align=\"left\"><a href=\"http://www.oxfordfunding.com.au/Panel-Shop-CashFlow-Solution.html\">Oxford Funding\'s Panel Shop Debtor Finance</a> funds the full value of your  invoices within 24 hours (less an agreed flat fee) so you can put your  cash to immediate and more efficient use.</p>\r\nOxford Funding also manages the collection of these invoices so you  don\'t need to spend time and resources to administer payments.\r\n<p align=\"left\">Oxford Funding is Australia’s largest provider of insurance and fleet  debtor finance and a subsidiary of Bendigo and Adelaide Bank Limited.</p>\r\n<p align=\"left\"><strong>How does it work?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>You fax invoices to Oxford, together with supporting documents as required.</li>\r\n	<li>Oxford accepts the invoices and pays up to 100% (less a small fee) by  EFT to your bank account, usually within 24 hours of initial receipt. A  two-hour funds transfer option is available at an extra cost.</li>\r\n	<li>We confirm with you the amount factored via fax or email.</li>\r\n	<li>You mail original invoice copies to our office in pre-paid envelopes supplied by us.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p align=\"left\"><strong>To find out how Oxford Funding’s Panel Shop Debtor Finance 